#selected "Goods-Prodicing" series from us employment dataset
us_emp <- us_employment %>%
  filter(Title == "Goods-Producing") %>%
  select(Month, Employed)

us_emp %>% 
  autoplot(Employed)

a .Produce an STL decomposition of the data and describe the trend and seasonality.

# plot STL decomposition
us_emp %>%
  model( STL(Employed) ) %>%
  components() %>%
  autoplot()

b.Do the data need transforming? If so, find a suitable transformation.

lambda <- us_emp %>%
  features( Employed, features = guerrero) %>%
  pull(lambda_guerrero)

bc_lambda = lambda

us_emp %>%
  autoplot(box_cox(Employed, lambda)) +
  labs(y = "",
       title = latex2exp::TeX(paste0(
         "US Employment Data with $\\lambda$=",
         round(lambda,4))))

  1. Identify a couple of ARIMA models that might be useful in describing the time series. Which of your models is the best according to their AICc values?
fit_emp <- us_emp %>%
  model(
    
    arima_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda)),
    arima_search_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda), stepwise = FALSE),
    arima100010_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(1,1,0) + PDQ(0,1,0)),
    arima012011_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(0,1,2) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    arima210011_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(2,1,0) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    arima011011_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(0,1,1) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    arima212011_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(2,1,2) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    arima210111_bc = ARIMA(box_cox(Employed, bc_lambda) ~ pdq(2,1,0) + PDQ(1,1,1))
 

    )

fit_emp %>% 
  pivot_longer(everything())

  1. Estimate the parameters of your best model and do diagnostic testing on the residuals. Do the residuals resemble white noise? If not, try to find another ARIMA model which fits better.
gg_tsresiduals(fit_emp %>% select(arima_search_bc), lag_max = 36)

# find degree of freedom

select(arima_search_bc) %>%
report()

# Ljung box test for white noise serires
augment(fit_emp) %>%
  filter(.model=="arima_search_bc") %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 10, dof = 6)

  1. Forecast the next 3 years of data. Get the latest figures from https://fred.stlouisfed.org/categories/11 to check the accuracy of your forecasts.
?us_employment

# Forecast the next 3 years
fit_emp %>%
  select(arima_search_bc) %>%
  forecast(h = "3 years") %>%
  autoplot(us_emp %>%
    filter(year(Month) >= 2000), level = 95
  )

accuracy(fit_emp) %>%
  arrange(RMSE) %>%
  select(.model, .type, RMSE, MAE, MAPE,)
